h3. Issue Summary
When using the old webui endpoint to preview a file attached to a page, it shows the actual JSON content instead of the file preview in the page.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# On the browser URL, run this API: {{https://SITE_NAME.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/content/search?cql=title%3D%22FILE_TITLE%22&expand=metadata,space}};
** Make sure to change the {{SITE_NAME}} and {{FILE_TITLE}} fields to your own information;
# Under {{_links}}, copy the endpoint from {{webui}} and paste it at the end of your site URL in the browser, like:
{{https://SITE_NAME.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/SPACEKEY/pages/PAGE_ID/File?preview=%2FPAGE_ID%2FFILE_ID%2FFILE_NAME}}

Another way to reproduce it is:
# Create a page in the old editor;
# Add a file text in the page;
# Publish the page;
# Click over the attached file to preview it;
# Refresh the page.

h3. Expected Results
The file preview is loaded on the Confluence page screen.
h3. Actual Results
The JSON content is shown in the browser.

*Notes*:
* If after step #2 the page loads fine, refresh it to face the bug;
* It seems that the old endpoint to view files in the Confluence UI ({{?preview=%2FPAGE_ID%2FFILE_ID%2FFILE_NAME}})is redirecting to the JSON content

h3. Workaround
When the JSON content gets shown, refresh the page to see the actual page and file.

h3. Issue Summary
When we insert more than an image, after publishing the page, the images we changed the size and set with left alignment will get smaller in the editing mode.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page;
# Insert an image - let's call it *Image A*;
# Set the image to be left-aligned;
# Let this image bigger than its original size;
# Publish the page;
# Edit the page - note the image is exactly how you set;
# Insert a new image (*Image B*);
# Set the size you want;
# Publish the page;
# Edit the page.

h3. Expected Results
The images are the way you set them: their size is alright.

h3. Actual Results
The *Image A* is smaller than you set in the first time.

*Note*:
* Looking at how *Image A* is set in the page's HTML for both published and draft pages, it is exactly the same size set, for example:
{code:html}<ac:image ac:align="left" ac:layout="align-start" ac:original-height="621" ac:original-width="729" ac:width="442"><ri:attachment ri:filename="Image-A.png" {code}
* Though the image is visibly smaller than the size we set, we can apply the changes on our page and then publish it - the size won't change in the published mode;
* It sounds a variation of this already fixed bug:
** [CONFCLOUD\-69403: Images such as small png icons inserted/pasted on a new editor page are not resizing/rendering correctly|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-69403]

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
The *Page Properties Report* macro is stopping to show the information from the *Contributors* macro when it is added within a *Page Properties*.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page called *Page I* and insert a *Page Properties* macro;
# Insert a table with two columns and two rows - name the headers as *A* and *B*;
# In the *A* column, insert the *Contributors* macro, and insert anything else on column *B*;
# Publish the page and add the label *contributors* on this page;
# Create a new page called *Page II* and insert the *Page Properties Report* macro;
# Set it to get the *contributors* label;
# Publish the page;
# Either refresh or access this page by logging in on an incognito window to access this page.

h3. Expected Results
The *Contributors* macro is shown with no issues

h3. Actual Results
Nothing is shown where the *Contributors* macro should be.

*Notes*:
* When the information is being shown on the page, the piece of HTML on the macro is:
{code:html}<div class="contributors-macro-ajax-container conf-macro output-block" data-hasbody="false" data-macro-name="contributors" data-macro-id="fee7d448-5418-48d3-9370-454b306cf08c" data-layout="default" resolved=""><div class="plugin-contributors"><div class="plugin-contributors"><span><span><a href="/wiki/display/~5f8dde29376a57006aef2a84" class="url fn">{code}
* When it is not showing:
{code:html}<div class="contributors-macro-ajax-container conf-macro output-block" data-hasbody="false" data-macro-name="contributors" data-macro-id="fee7d448-5418-48d3-9370-454b306cf08c" data-layout="default"><div style="display: none;" class="contributors-macro-parameters">{"noneFoundMessage":"<None>","limit":"1","showLastTime":"true","contentType":"pages","order":"update","contextEntityId":846069777}</div></div>{code}
* It seems like a regression of the following already fixed bug: [CONFCLOUD\-53816: Page properties report broken when Contributors macro|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-53816]

h3. Workaround
Navigate to the page where the *Page Properties* with the *Contributors* macro is and then go back to the report page
*OR*
Access the editing mode of the report page and then close it.

h3. Issue Summary
Copying and pasting two or more paragraphs inside an Expand macro would actually result in just one paragraph being pasted

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a Blank page and add an Expand macro (/Expand);
 # Add two paragraphs of text inside of the Expand macro(got mine from https://www.lipsum.com/feed/html);
 # Select both paragraphs and copy them;
 # Paste them inside of the Expand Macro;

h3. Expected Results
* Both Paragraphs to be pasted inside the macro;

h3. Actual Results
* Just a single paragraph is pasted, even though we copied both of them.
This behavior can be seen in this next GIF:

 !Screen Recording 2020-11-17 at 11.25 AM.gif! 
h3. Workaround
* Copy one paragraph at a time, as this BUG seems to affect copying/pasting more than one paragraph at once.

h3. Issue Summary
* When creating a new Blog Post Confluence ends up creating an extra page draft, that is not associated with the Blog Post itself, creating clutter on customers' instances. When the Blog Post is published there would be an extra draft (accessible by clicking on *Recent* > Drafts) that was created when the Blog Post template was selected.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Click on *Create* button (or hit 'C' on your keyboard);
 # On the right panel chose the "Blog Template";
 # Add a title to the Blog Post and publish it;
 # Navigate to space home, or instance home, or just refresh the page (Just so Confluence can update the recently updated/create pages);
 # click on *Recent* button (next to Home) > Click on *Drafts*
 # Check out the most recent draft.

h3. Expected Results
* As a Blog Post was published, no extra draft should have been created;

h3. Actual Results
* Both a Blog Post was created, as well as an extra draft, this behavior can be seen in this next GIF:


h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available;
(i) Users can clean up their *Drafts* by accessing: *Recent* > *Drafts* > and removing them one by one (by accessing the draft, clicking *...* > "Delete Unpublished Changes")

h3. Issue Summary
In the Confluence Cloud Document ["Configure the indexing language"|https://support.atlassian.com/confluence-cloud/docs/configure-the-indexing-language/], the steps to complete the action are listed, however, this action can only be performed by a "System Administrator", There is a note about this at the top of the page, however it is misleading as it referance the permission needed to perform the action without context that the permission noted in cloud sites is the "System Administrator" permissions or "SYSADMIN" and this permission is a restricted group in Cloud sites  (Detailed further in [“Functional differences in Confluence Cloud”)|https://confluence.atlassian.com/confcloud/restricted-functions-in-confluence-cloud-734070955.html] and Only Atlassian Support can make this configuration change, and it is not available for Confluence Site Admins to do on their own and causes confusion that the function should be available for them to configure with the appropriate permission.

Additionally, there is a Grammar / Typo issue in the warning info pane, Noting that only system administrators can perform this action,  which reads:
{quote}
Currently, you can only can change indexing language and reindex all documents if you are a sysadmin. Otherwise, you have to contact Atlassian Support.
{quote}

The portion that reads
{quote}
"you can only can change"
{quote}
Should read 
{quote}
you can only change
{quote}

h3. Suggested Resolution:
As this is a feature that can only be configured by Atlassian Support in a Cloud instance the Configuration steps should only Note the following without steps for the configuration options as it leads to false expectations:
{quote}
"Currently on Confluence Cloud Sites, this feature can only be configured by Atlassian Support.  Please contact us at https://support.atlassian.com/contact ,  noting what indexing language you would like to have set on your behalf and add the link to this Document in your request for reference"

We are tracking an update to this functionality at the following Feature Request:
- https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-65935
{quote}

h3. NOTE:
Additional steps need to be given for Cloud Free users as they will not be able to create the support request directly and would need to file a request under billing and licensing to contact Customer Advocates and request a redirect to the Confluence Cloud Support to make the configuration change on their behalf

{panel:title=Status Update 22 April 2020|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ff7f7f|titleBGColor=#ff7f7f|bgColor=#e5e5e5}
Hi everyone,

Thank you again for your feedback as we worked on fixing the original version of this bug related to duplicating tasks when copying a page. We recognize that some of you are experiencing a related bug, where the task report macro is currently duplicating some tasks depending on how its pagination is set. We are tracking reports of this bug's occurrence on at https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-72026. You can follow along the ticket there as the source of truth. Thank you again for your feedback!

Best,
Sunny Xu

{panel}

h3. Issue Summary

Working with tasks on Confluence is a great way to keep tracking our daily job! Sometimes, on an existing page that already contains a determined format, we can copy it and then just change the tasks' description, in order to make our life easier - though, doing this is currently making the Task Report macro to behave unexpectedly.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page called *Report* and add a Task Report macro;
 # In the same space you created the above page, create a new one called *Tasks*;
 # Add a few tasks with random names there (3 tasks are enough) and publish the page;
 # Copy *Tasks*;
 # In the *Copy of Tasks*, change the text from the three tasks and publish the page;
 # Go to the *Report* page.

h3. Expected Results

The Task Report macro shows all the distinct tasks from both pages;
h3. Actual Results

The Task Report macro duplicate the tasks that got their name changed on the copied page. It also happens in the tasks session, on the user profile.

*Notes*:
 * If on step #5 you actually remove the tasks and publish the page without any task, in the report macro/user profile tasks, they are shown with the old name in the copied page.

h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
When filtering a Version Picker custom field in Jira on a Jira Issue macro, in Confluence, it will not display the value of this field.


h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Step  In Jira, choose Settings >> Issues;
 # Step 2 Select Fields >> Custom fields
 # Step 3 Click on Add custom field;
 # Step 4 Click on Advanced >> Version picker field
 # Step 5 Give a name to it and click on the Create button;
 # Step 6 Create an issue in Jira and add this field to it;
 # Step 7 In Confluence, create a page;
 # Step 8 On the Confluence page, insert a Jira Issue macro;
 # Step 9 On the macro's settings, click on Display options, On the Columns to display field,  # Step 10 type the name that was given to the Jira custom field and Click on the Insert button ans Publish the page;

h3. Expected Results
Confluence will display the value of the column associated with the version Picker custom field.
h3. Actual Results
Confluence is not displaying the value of the column associated with the version Picker custom field.
 !image-2020-11-13-13-53-46-544.png|thumbnail! 
h3. Workaround
 Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available
